    <segment id="1" parent="33" relname="span">
A good system should, ideally, be able to recover from errors with no user intervention</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="19" relname="span"> - otherwise it becomes &quot;error reporting&quot;</segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="12" relname="condition"> if it waits for a user to take action.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="19" relname="elaboration"> Practically, very minimal user intervention should occur.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="31" relname="background"> I love to pick on Windows.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="14" relname="volitional-cause"> Remember the famous Windows95,98 error message &quot;THIS PROGRAM HAS PERFOMED AN ILLEGAL OPERATION&quot;</segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="35" relname="span"> - so? .</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="23" relname="span">That message was very uninformatives</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="15" relname="volitional-cause"> and just for curiosity&apos;s sake, if you click the DETAILS button,</segment>
    <segment id="15" parent="21" relname="span"> you would get a bunch of meaningless number.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="22" relname="span"> So why display the error message </segment>
    <segment id="16" parent="6" relname="circumstance">if the details further confuse the user?</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="30" relname="span"> Microsoft apparently did a very good job with Windows XP.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="17" relname="condition"> If you get an error message on Windows XP,</segment>
    <segment id="17" parent="27" relname="span"> mostly its; &quot;WINDOWS HAS RECOVERED FROM A SERIOUS ERROR&quot;.</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="26" relname="span"> Thats much better!</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="25" relname="span"> all I need is to keep working,</segment>
    <segment id="18" parent="9" relname="antithesis"> not to stop and wonder what I should do with an error message.</segment>
